%EOM----------------------

%BOM---------------------
Date:4/12/2009 4:48:18 PM
From:Dale Baker
Ratings agencies are legally classified as media outlets, no different than Jim
Cramer ranting every day on CNBC. They aren't registered investment advisors,
hence they have no fiduciary responsibility to anyone, now are they regulated
(unless they tried to start trading for themselves while they kept issuing
ratings, which would bring the SEC down on them pretty quickly - ).
%EOM----------------------

%BOM---------------------
Date:4/12/2009 5:17:10 PM
From:Dale Baker
now are they regulated

Should read "nor are they regulated"...not yet, at least.
%EOM----------------------

%BOM---------------------
Date:4/12/2009 5:32:21 PM
From:Madharry
no disrespect intended but if they are legally classified as media outlets,
could legal documents tying collateral, interest rates, and debt repayment
schedules to ratings by media outlets be legal enforced? I can tell you the
money center bank that employed me for seven years treated the rating agencies
as god like figures. We were told that we were not to review AAA rated credits,
as by definition there was no chance of default. of course this was in the 90s
and before the days of loan slicing and dicing.
%EOM----------------------

%BOM---------------------
Date:4/12/2009 5:40:02 PM
From:Dale Baker
It's no different than a library that refuses to carry any book that hasn't
been reviewed in the New York Times; the library's purchases are clearly linked
to NYT reviews, but the NYT isn't offering anything more than their opinion on
the books, good or bad, not a specific buy or sell recommendation.

That's why ratings agencies use terms like positive and negative instead of buy
and sell. They are simply guessing at future creditworthiness. What you do with
their guesses is your business.
